<h2>Quick Verdict</h2>

<p>
The AKT1 Blackout earbuds combine electronic hearing protection,
Bluetooth audio capability, and a compact in-ear design that works well
for range use. The biggest takeaway from this review is that the
fit matters a lot: once inserted properly, they feel much more secure
and effective than a casual first try might suggest.
</p>

<p>
They also work well for general range communication and situational
awareness, but Bluetooth latency creates limitations when trying to use
them as part of a precision shot timer setup.
</p>

<h2>What Makes This Review Different</h2>

<p>
This review focuses on two practical issues that matter in real use:
getting the earbuds inserted correctly and testing how they behave when
paired with a Bluetooth-enabled shot timer.
</p>

<p>
The fit tip is especially important because it changes how secure the
earbuds feel and how well they perform. The Bluetooth timer test is also
useful because it highlights a real limitation that is easy to overlook.
</p>

<h2>Why These Were Chosen</h2>

<p>
The Blackout earbuds were selected as part of a move away from older
wired range audio setups and bulkier over-ear hearing protection.
</p>

<p>
They stood out because of their 25 dB noise reduction, hearing
enhancement, compact size, and the ability to wear them on their own
or under over-ear protection if desired.
</p>

<h2>Fit and Insertion Technique</h2>

<p>
The fit is one of the most important parts of the Blackout experience.
Simply pushing the earbuds into the ear is not enough to get the best
result.
</p>

<p>
The insertion method demonstrated in the video is to begin with the left
or right indicator facing upright, insert the earbud into the ear, and
then rotate it backward into place.
</p>

<p>
That rotation helps the earbud lock in more securely and made a
noticeable difference in comfort, stability, and overall performance
during use.
</p>

<h2>Noise Reduction and Hearing Enhancement</h2>

<p>
The Blackout earbuds reduce loud impulse noise while amplifying
lower-level sounds. This allows gunfire to be reduced while still
hearing conversations and range commands.
</p>

<p>
The hearing enhancement feature is useful for range communication
without constantly removing hearing protection.
</p>

<h2>Bluetooth and Shot Timer Testing</h2>

<p>
Testing included pairing the earbuds with a Bluetooth shot timer
workflow through a smartphone.
</p>

<p>
This introduced too much Bluetooth latency for precision timing
drills. The signal delay meant the beep reached the ears after the
timer had already started counting.
</p>

<p>
It can still work as a simple start signal, but for drills requiring
precise timing the Bluetooth delay becomes a limitation.
</p>

<h2>Comfort and Real-World Use</h2>

<p>
Once fitted correctly the earbuds were comfortable enough to wear for
extended range sessions and were easy to forget about during use.
</p>

<p>
The compact charging case also makes them easy to carry and the
included foam tips allow fit adjustment.
</p>

<h2>Who These Earbuds May Be For</h2>

<ul>
<li>People wanting compact electronic hearing protection</li>
<li>Those who prefer in-ear protection to over-ear muffs</li>
<li>Shooters who want Bluetooth audio capability</li>
<li>Users who value situational awareness at the range</li>
</ul>

<h2>Key Takeaways</h2>

<ul>
<li>Proper insertion technique greatly improves fit</li>
<li>Secure once rotated into place</li>
<li>Compact and comfortable design</li>
<li>Good range communication capability</li>
<li>Bluetooth delay limits precise shot timer use</li>
</ul>

